    "When an argument infers cause from a before-after change, it must assume no other coinciding change produced the effect. Here the argument needs that nothing else (new chairs, ergonomics training, seasonal factors) caused the 30% drop. The negation test confirms it: if another change caused the drop, the standing-desk conclusion fails. Strong or off-topic claims are not necessary.",
